\textit{Source: Bojko--Lim--Moreira, Section 2.3.}
  For \(k \geq -1\), the \emph{Virasoro operator} is
  \[\bL_k \coloneqq \bR_k + \bT_k \colon \BD^X \to \BD^X.\]

\textit{Source: Bojko--Lim--Moreira, Section 2.5.}
  For \(k \geq -1\), the \emph{pair Virasoro operator}
  \(\bL_k^\pa \colon \Dpa \to \Dpa\) is \(\bL_k^\pa = \bR_k^\pa + \bT_k^\pa\),
  where:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item \(\bR_k^\pa = \bR_k \otimes \mathrm{id} + \mathrm{id} \otimes \bR_k\)
        (a derivation on \(\Dpa\));
  \item \(\bT_k^\pa\) is multiplication by
        \(\displaystyle\sum_{i+j=k} (-1)^{\dim X - p^L}\, i!\, j!\,
          \chh_i^{F-V}\, \chh_j^F(\tdX)\),
        with \(\chh_i^{F-V} \coloneqq \chh_i^F - \chh_i^V\).
  \end{enumerate}
  The pair Virasoro operators \(\bL_k^V \colon \BD^X \to \BD^X\) for a fixed
  sheaf \(V\) are obtained from \(\bL_k^\pa\) via the factoring map
  \(\xi_V \colon \Dpa \to \BD^X\).

\textit{Source: Bojko--Lim--Moreira, Section 3.2 (following Kac \cite{Ka98}).}
  A \emph{vertex algebra} is a \(\mathbb{Z}\)-graded \(\mathbb{C}\)-vector space
  \(V_\bullet\) equipped with:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item a \emph{vacuum vector} \(|0\rangle \in V_0\);
  \item a \emph{translation operator} \(T \colon V_\bullet \to V_{\bullet+2}\);
  \item a \emph{state-field correspondence}
        \(Y(-,z) \colon V_\bullet \to \mathrm{End}(V_\bullet)[\![z,z^{-1}]\!]\),
        written \(Y(a,z) = \sum_{n \in \mathbb{Z}} a_{(n)} z^{-n-1}\),
        where \(a_{(n)} \colon V_\bullet \to V_{\bullet + \deg(a) - 2n - 2}\).
  \end{enumerate}
  These must satisfy:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Vacuum}: \(T|0\rangle = 0\), \(Y(|0\rangle, z) = \mathrm{id}\),
        \(Y(a,z)|0\rangle \in a + z V_\bullet[\![z]\!]\);
  \item \textbf{Translation covariance}: \([T, Y(a,z)] = \tfrac{d}{dz} Y(a,z)\);
  \item \textbf{Locality}: for all \(a, b \in V_\bullet\), there exists \(N \gg 0\)
        such that \((z-w)^N [Y(a,z), Y(b,w)] = 0\).
  \end{enumerate}

\textit{Source: Bojko--Lim--Moreira, Section 3.2.}
  A \emph{conformal element} in a vertex algebra \(V_\bullet\) is a vector
  \(\omega \in V_4\) such that the Fourier modes \(L_n \coloneqq \omega_{(n+1)}\),
  defined by \(Y(\omega, z) = \sum_{n \in \mathbb{Z}} L_n z^{-n-2}\), satisfy:
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item the Virasoro bracket:
        \([L_n, L_m] = (n-m) L_{m+n} + \tfrac{n^3-n}{12} \delta_{n+m,0} \cdot C\)
        for some \emph{central charge} \(C \in \mathbb{C}\);
  \item \(L_{-1} = T\);
  \item \(L_0\) is diagonalizable (its eigenspaces give the conformal grading
        \(V_\bullet^\omega\)).
  \end{enumerate}
  A vertex algebra with a conformal element is called a \emph{vertex operator algebra}
  (VOA).
